<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="254" pageId="14" pageNumber="253" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1820,2027]" lastBlockId="15.[151,1437,150,430]" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="254" pageId="14" pageNumber="253">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1928,1954]" pageId="14" pageNumber="253">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fitzgerald" authorityYear="2020" box="[328,495,1929,1954]" class="Insecta" family="Ditomyiidae" genus="Ditomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="253" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nana">
<emphasis box="[328,495,1929,1954]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="253">Ditomyia nana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other New World 
<taxonomicName box="[995,1099,1929,1954]" class="Insecta" family="Ditomyiidae" genus="Ditomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="253" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[995,1099,1929,1954]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="253">Ditomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characters: Small size (wing ca. 
<quantity box="[538,640,1964,1991]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.25" pageId="14" pageNumber="253" unit="mm" value="3.25">3.25 mm</quantity>
), wings hyaline, r-m crossvein absent, with Rs, stem of M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1280,1305,1983,1997]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="253">1+2</subScript>
, and bm-cu crossvein meeting in a point (
<figureCitation box="[476,558,2000,2026]" captionStart="FIGURES 38–39" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1948,1972]" captionTargetBox="[230,1361,454,1921]" captionTargetId="figure-111@15.[227,1361,453,1925]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 38–39. D. nana, n. sp., holotype male. 38. Habitus, lateral. 39. Wing. Scale bars = ca. 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4412997" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4412997/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="253">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
), vertex of head distinctly bulging and elevated (
<figureCitation box="[1096,1232,2000,2026]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–41" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1223,1247]" captionTargetBox="[240,1347,181,1198]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[240,1347,181,1199]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 40–41. D. nana n. sp., head. 40. Male, holotype, anterior view. 41. Female, paratype, lateral view. Scale bars = ca. 0.25 mm. Abbreviations: fs, frontal suture; lo, lateral ocellus; mo, median ocellus; mp1, maxillary palpus one; mp2, maxillary palpus two; v, vertex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4412999" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4412999/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="253">Figs. 40–41</figureCitation>
), maxillary palpus two-segmented, male terminalia as 
<figureCitation box="[546,680,150,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 42–46" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[235,1352,669,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-225@17.[234,1352,669,1865]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 42–46. D. nana n. sp., terminalia. 42–45. Male, holotype. 42. Lateral. 43. Close-up of serrated edge on gonostylus, ventrolateral. 44. Dorsal. 45. Ventral. 46. Female, paratype, lateral. Scale bars = ca. 0.25 mm, except Fig. 43 scale bar = ca. 0.05 mm. Abbreviations: c, cerci; c1, cercus one; c2, cercus two; gc, gonocoxite; gs, gonostylus; h, hypandrium; hl, hypandrial lobe; p, paramere; s8, sternite eight; t9, tergite nine." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4413001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4413001/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="254">Figs. 42–45</figureCitation>
, female terminalia as 
<figureCitation box="[922,1001,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 42–46" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[235,1352,669,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-225@17.[234,1352,669,1865]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 42–46. D. nana n. sp., terminalia. 42–45. Male, holotype. 42. Lateral. 43. Close-up of serrated edge on gonostylus, ventrolateral. 44. Dorsal. 45. Ventral. 46. Female, paratype, lateral. Scale bars = ca. 0.25 mm, except Fig. 43 scale bar = ca. 0.05 mm. Abbreviations: c, cerci; c1, cercus one; c2, cercus two; gc, gonocoxite; gs, gonostylus; h, hypandrium; hl, hypandrial lobe; p, paramere; s8, sternite eight; t9, tergite nine." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4413001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4413001/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="254">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
with ultimate segment of cerci broadly rounded.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="254" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,150,430]" pageId="15" pageNumber="254">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,223,249]" pageId="15" pageNumber="254">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[325,429,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Ditomyiidae" genus="Ditomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[325,429,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="254">Ditomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been considered a strictly Holarctic group and the several “Neotropical 
<taxonomicName box="[1320,1424,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Ditomyiidae" genus="Ditomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1320,1424,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="254">Ditomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” species previously described have ultimately been reassigned to other genera (e.g. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Freeman, 1951)" baseAuthorityName="Freeman" baseAuthorityYear="1951" class="Insecta" family="Ditomyiidae" genus="Nervijuncta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conjuncta">
<emphasis box="[1106,1358,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="254">Nervijuncta conjuncta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Freeman, P." pageId="15" pageNumber="254" pagination="1 - 138" refId="ref10987" refString="Freeman, P. (1951) Mycetophilidae. In: Diptera of Patagonia and South Chile based mainly on material in the British Museum (Natural History). 3. British Museum of Natural History, London, pp. 1 - 138." type="book chapter" year="1951">Freeman, 1951</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Giglio-Tos, 1890)" baseAuthorityName="Giglio-Tos" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[298,856,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Ditomyiidae" genus="Australosymmerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis box="[298,634,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="254">Australosymmerus mexicanus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Giglio-Tos, E." box="[652,848,295,321]" pageId="15" pageNumber="254" pagination="84" refId="ref11072" refString="Giglio-Tos, E. (1890) Nuove species di Ditteri del Museo Zoologico di Torino. Bollettino Musei di Zoologia ed Anatomia comparata della R. Universita di Torino, 5 (84). [no pagination]" type="journal article" year="1890">Giglio-Tos, 1890</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Giglio-Tos, 1890)" baseAuthorityName="Giglio-Tos" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[916,1260,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Ditomyiidae" genus="Australosymmerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zonatus">
<emphasis box="[916,1036,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="254">A. zonatus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Giglio-Tos, E." box="[1053,1252,295,321]" pageId="15" pageNumber="254" pagination="84" refId="ref11072" refString="Giglio-Tos, E. (1890) Nuove species di Ditteri del Museo Zoologico di Torino. Bollettino Musei di Zoologia ed Anatomia comparata della R. Universita di Torino, 5 (84). [no pagination]" type="journal article" year="1890">Giglio-Tos, 1890</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
; Monroe 1974, 
<bibRefCitation author="Papavero, N." box="[151,325,331,357]" pageId="15" pageNumber="254" pagination="1 - 6" refId="ref11681" refString="Papavero, N. (1977) Fascicle 19 B. Family Ditomyiidae. In: Papavero, N. (Ed.), A Catalogue of the Diptera of the Americas south of the United States. Museu de Zoologia, Sao Paulo, pp. 1 - 6." type="book chapter" year="1977">Papavero 1977</bibRefCitation>
). However, after comparison with characters of all other ditomyiid genera, 
<taxonomicName authority="Fitzgerald, 2020" authorityName="Fitzgerald" authorityYear="2020" box="[1195,1364,331,356]" class="Insecta" family="Ditomyiidae" genus="Ditomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nana" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1195,1364,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="254">Ditomyia nana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1374,1436,331,357]" pageId="15" pageNumber="254" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is tentatively placed in the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[529,633,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Ditomyiidae" genus="Ditomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[529,633,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="254">Ditomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and compared to the similar genera 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marshall" authorityYear="1896" box="[1047,1179,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Ditomyiidae" genus="Nervijuncta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1047,1179,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="254">Nervijuncta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saigusa" authorityYear="1973" box="[1236,1384,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Ditomyiidae" genus="Asioditomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1236,1384,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="254">Asioditomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see “Discussion”).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
